ce:section.ce:para:
Figure 4C depicts the variation of Li-ion concentration in the active electrode-electrolyte along the thickness direction (y/l

   a
) and the contour map of Li-ion distribution in the active electrode-electrolyte. From Figure 4C, it can be seen that at similar depth of discharge (DOD) levels, the 40 μm active electrode shows a significant difference in Li-ion concentration between the separator side and the current collector side. In contrast, the 10-μm active electrode exhibits almost no difference in Li-ion concentration between the separator side and the current collector side. Additionally, the 10-μm electrode shows minimal differences in Li-ion concentration in the electrolyte at different C-rates, whereas the differences increase with electrode thickness. The concentration difference in the electrolyte between the separator side and the current collector side grows with increasing electrode thickness, and this phenomenon is exacerbated by higher C-rates. However, the impact of C-rates on the concentration difference between the two ends is less significant than the impact of electrode thickness. The primary reason for this phenomenon is that thicker electrodes have longer Li-ion migration distances, and the expansion of Si can block some pathways, further hindering Li-ion migration and leading to greater concentration polarization. Additionally, in thick electrodes, the active particles near the separator side have a higher degree of lithiation, leading to greater volumetric expansion in this region. This increased expansion is more likely to block the migration pathways, making it more difficult for Li-ions to migrate toward the current collector side. Consequently, thick electrodes exhibit higher-concentration polarization and poorer cycling performance during charge-discharge cycles.

Figures 6A and 6D respectively show the variations in tangential stress (σ

   T
) and normal stress (σ

   n
) at the interface between the active electrode and the current collector with changes in DOD, where r/R denotes the ratio of the position on the active electrode-collector interface to the radius of the pole piece. From Figures 6A and 6D it is evident that with the increase in lithiation depth, significant changes occur at the edge of the interface between the active electrode and the current collector. This is attributed to the greater volumetric expansion of the active electrode during lithiation, which causes higher stress due to the deformation coordination between the active electrode and the current collector. In Figures 6B and 6E, it can be observed that at the outer edge of the electrode, the interface stress undergoes substantial changes. This phenomenon is due to the mismatch in deformation between the current collector and the active electrode, as well as the uneven concentration distribution in the thickness direction, which leads to the bending of the electrode edge toward the current collector. However, due to constraints at the boundary and the free side edge, the electrode cannot complete the bending, resulting in significant stress concentration at the edge. As the thickness of the active electrode increases from 10 μm to 20 μm and then to 40 μm, the tangential stress and normal stress at the interface markedly increase. Although the normal stress here is in a compressive state, it can be observed that the stress at the edges is very high, which does not prevent electrode delamination but rather causes adhesive failure at the edges. From Figure 6C and 6F, which show the tangential and normal displacements, it can be seen that the tangential displacement is several orders of magnitude greater than the normal displacement. This indicates that the tangential stress is the dominant factor in the cracking of the active electrode and the current collector. The thicker the electrode, the greater the stress at the edges, making the boundaries more prone to delamination. Thicker electrodes result in more concentrated edge stress, increasing the risk of cracking at the interface, thereby deteriorating the effective contact between the active electrode and the current collector. During repeated lithiation-delithiation cycles, this delamination of the active electrode leads to capacity loss. For a 40-μm-thick electrode at C-rates of 0.1, 0.3, and 0.5 C, the differences in tangential stress and normal stress at the interface between the current collector and the active electrode are minimal. The stress contour plots (as shown in Figure 6G) also show that compared to the separator and the active electrode, the current collector exhibits a larger stress distribution. From the von Mises stress contour map shown in Figure 6G, it can be observed that the maximum von Mises stress occurs on the current collector, with the highest values located at the edges of the current collector and the active electrode. Additionally, as the thickness increases, the von Mises stress shows a significant variation, whereas changes in the C-rate have a minimal impact on the von Mises stress. This indicates that the mechanical stability of the electrode is more sensitive to changes in thickness rather than C-rate performance. The deterioration in mechanical stability exacerbates the decline in battery cycle performance, resulting in reduced capacity retention.
